      "question": "The pair of equations $\\frac{2}{x} + \\frac{3}{y} = 13$ and $\\frac{5}{x} - \\frac{4}{y} = -2$ can be reduced to a linear system in $u$ and $v$ by substituting $u = \\frac{1}{x}$ and $v = \\frac{1}{y}$. If the resulting system is $2u + 3v = 13$ and $5u - 4v = -2$, what is the value of $x + y$?",
      "answer": "(A)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Substitute $u = 1/x$ and $v = 1/y$ to get the linear system: $2u + 3v = 13$ (eq 1) and $5u - 4v = -2$ (eq 2).",
          "Multiply (eq 1) by 4 and (eq 2) by 3: $8u + 12v = 52$ and $15u - 12v = -6$.",
          "Add the two equations: $23u = 46$, which gives $u = 2$.",
          "Substitute $u = 2$ into (eq 1): $2(2) + 3v = 13 \\Rightarrow 3v = 9 \\Rightarrow v = 3$.",
          "Find $x$ and $y$: $x = 1/u = 1/2$ and $y = 1/v = 1/3$.",
          "Calculate $x + y = 1/2 + 1/3 = 3/6 + 2/6 = 5/6$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$2u + 3v = 13 \\quad (1) \\\\ 5u - 4v = -2 \\quad (2) \\\\ (2u + 3v) \\times 4 \\Rightarrow 8u + 12v = 52 \\\\ (5u - 4v) \\times 3 \\Rightarrow 15u - 12v = -6 \\\\ 23u = 46 \\Rightarrow u = 2 \\\\ 2(2) + 3v = 13 \\Rightarrow 3v = 9 \\Rightarrow v = 3 \\\\ x = \\frac{1}{2}, y = \\frac{1}{3} \\\\ x + y = \\frac{1}{2} + \\frac{1}{3} = \\frac{5}{6}$"
      },
